The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 State-run teaching hospitals and their surroundings turned out to be among the noisiest places in the city on Kali puja night. A three-member team of the pollution control board ? including high court-appointed special officer on noise pollution Biswajit Mukherjee ? realised this after inspecting the medical colleges on Tuesday. The team?s first stop was SSKM Hospital, where employees and their relatives were organising a puja on the premises. They played loudspeakers at earsplitting volume and burst banned crackers. The fireworks were seized and the secretary of the organising committee, Shyam Mallik, was handed over to police. 

 t NRS Medical College, too, a puja was being held. Though there were no blaring loudspeakers, crackers were burst unchecked. The team asked the organisers to observe a quiet Diwali. SSKM superintendent Santanu Tripathi promised action against the guilty and NRS deputy-superintendent D.K. Jha said steps would be taken to ensure that patients were not troubled.

 n related developments, four men were arrested across the city on Monday night for transporting banned crackers.

 Raju Mullick, a newspaper vendor, was killed after the bicycle he was riding was hit by a private bus on route 217 on Ultadanga Road, under the footbridge, around 5.50 am on Tuesday. Another vendor, Asim Chowdhury, accompanying Raju on another bicycle, was critically injured. He was admitted to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital. The driver fled with the vehicle. 

 Samir Dasgupta, 26, an alleged criminal, was arrested on Tollygunge Road, under the Lake police station area, in a pre-dawn raid on Monday. A firearm and a round of cartridge were seized from Samir, alias Handle. The raid was led by officer-in-charge Sukumar Chakraborty.

 The Howrah Municipal Corporation on Tuesday started draining out stagnant water from the Bellilious Lane area and desilting the blocked drains. The civic employees were helped by local residents. Calcutta High Court, acting on a petition by Howrah Ganatantrik Nagarik Samity, asked the civic body on Monday to start the drive by Tuesday. 

 Chief secretary Amit Kiran Deb will chair a meeting on November 9 to finalise the details of the proposed Wetland Interpretation Centre at East Calcutta Wetlands. Deb heads a committee which is framing a policy on the conservation of wetlands, declared a Ramsar site. 

 The state government is preparing for moving the office of the chief electoral officer (CEO) out of Writers? Buildings. The CEO will sit either in the West Bengal Industrial Development Corporation building in BBD Bag or at 4, Camac Street. The issue was discussed on Tuesday by chief secretary Amit Kiran Deb, PWD secretary Kalyani Chowdhury and CEO Debashish Sen.

 Members of Nepali Janadhikar Suraksha Samiti alleged on Tuesday that thousands of Nepalis are being forced to flee to India because of the ?horrifying poverty, unemployment and backwardness in Nepal?. Blaming the monarchy for the situation, the organisation has resolved to extend moral support to political forces fighting for democracy in Nepal. This was announced by Laxman Pant, president of the Samiti?s central committee on Tuesday.

 Residents of Motilal Nehru Road, in ward 85, lodged a police complaint on Tuesday against criminal activities in the locality. Recently, a huge cache of arms and ammunition was seized from a TV repair shop in the area.

